          "body": "Three times in Nehemiah's memoir the phrase 'the hand of my God' appears (vv. 8, 18; cf. 1:10), and each occurrence is the author's interpretive key to what the surrounding narrative means. When Artaxerxes grants letters, military escort, and timber requisitions to a Jewish cupbearer who asked for leave to go rebuild a city — that is not diplomacy. That is the hand of God on a pagan king. Ezra uses the identical formula repeatedly (Ezra 7:6, 9, 28; 8:18, 22, 31), and the shared language ties the two books together as a single theological argument: the God of heaven is not a local deity confined to the restored temple. He governs imperial courts, provincial governors, and forest keepers. Calvin's commentary on Nehemiah stresses that the sovereign God uses human instruments without coercing them; Artaxerxes acts freely and God acts sovereignly through that free action simultaneously. The same hand Nehemiah prays to in the gap between question and answer (v. 4) is the hand he credits when the king says yes (v. 8) and reports to the people when they need a reason to build (v. 18)."
